ğŸ”¹ Java Config Bean (@Configuration + @Bean)
We already saw this method, where we explicitly told Spring:

@Configuration
public class AppConfig {
    @Bean
    public Chef chef() {
        return new Chef();
    }
}
ğŸ”¹ Using @Component and @Autowired (More common in Spring Boot)
Here we donâ€™t need to write a config class. Instead, we let Spring auto-detect beans with @Component.

Step 1: Mark Chef as a Spring Bean
package com.example.demo;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@Component  // Spring will automatically create and manage this bean
public class Chef {
    public void cookFood() {
        System.out.println("Chef is cooking delicious food!");
    }
}
Step 2: Create another class that depends on Chef
package com.example.demo;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service  // Marks this as a service bean
public class Restaurant {

    private final Chef chef;

    // Spring automatically injects the Chef bean here
    public Restaurant(Chef chef) {
        this.chef = chef;
    }

    public void serveFood() {
        chef.cookFood();
        System.out.println("Restaurant is serving food to customers!");
    }
}
Step 3: Use it in the Spring Boot main app
package com.example.demo;

import org.springframework.boot.CommandLineRunner;
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

@SpringBootApplication
public class DemoApplication implements CommandLineRunner {

    private final Restaurant restaurant;

    // Spring injects Restaurant bean automatically
    public DemoApplication(Restaurant restaurant) {
        this.restaurant = restaurant;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args);
    }

    @Override
    public void run(String... args) {
        restaurant.serveFood();
    }
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:
Chef is cooking delicious food!
Restaurant is serving food to customers!
ğŸ”¹ Real-Life Analogy
@Component â†’ You put a Chef badge on a person so the manager (Spring) knows heâ€™s a Chef.

@Autowired (or constructor injection) â†’ Whenever a Restaurant is built, the manager automatically assigns a Chef to it.

ğŸ‘‰ Summary:

@Configuration + @Bean â†’ You manually define beans in a config class. (Explicit control)

@Component + @Autowired â†’ Spring auto-scans and wires beans for you. (Most common in Spring Boot)

